abstract.title: ABSTRACT
Objective
abstract.p: To systematically review the biomechanical deficits after anterior cruciate ligamentACL reconstruction (ACLR) during single leg hop for distance (SLHD) testing and report these differences compared tocompared with the contralateral leg and to with healthy controls.
abstract.title: Design Systematic systematic review with meta-analysis.
Data sources
abstract.p: A systematic search in Pubmed (Ovid), EMBASE, CINAHL, Scopus, Web of Science, PEDro, SPORTDiscus, Cochrane Library, grey literature and trial registries, was conducted from inception to 1 April 1st first 2018.
abstract.title: Eligibility criteria for selecting studies
abstract.p: Studies reporting kinematic, kinetic, and/or electromyographic (EMG) data of the ACLR limb during SLHD with no language limits.

The literature review yielded 1551 articles and 19 studies met the inclusion criteria. Meta-analysis revealed strong evidence of lower peak knee flexion angle and knee flexion moments during landing compared with the uninjured leg and with controls. Also, moderate evidence (with large effect size) of lower knee power absorption during landing compared with the uninjured leg. No difference was found in peak vertical ground reaction force during landing. Subgroup analyses revealed that some kinematic variables do not restore with time and may even worsen.
abstract.title: Conclusion
abstract.p: During SLHD several kinematic and kinetic deficits were detected between limbs after ACLR, despite adequate SLHD performance. Measuring only hop distance, even using the healthy leg as a reference, is insufficient to fully assess knee function after ACLR.

body.title: INTRODUCTION
body.p: Anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) injury is associated with a high injury burden in terms of days lost from sports participation.1 Despite current advances in ACL reconstruction (ACLR) techniques, more than a third of those who receive surgery are unable to return to preinjury levels of activity.2 In addition, reinjury rate after ACLR is high with around 20% of young athletes reinjuring the operated side or suffering an ACL rupture in the contralateral (healthy) knee within a year of returning to play.3

After an ACL reconstruction, lower limb biomechanics are altered, both in the frontal (increased hip adduction and knee valgus) and the sagittal plane (decreased hip extension and knee flexion moments), and in both legs.4 These movement patterns and loading strategies are associated with increased risk of a non-contact ACL injury.5 6

While detailed biomechanical evaluations using advanced techniques such as three-dimensional motion analyses, force plate measurements and electromyography (EMG) are available in the research context, the clinical criteria to determine readiness for return to play (RTP) typically rely on a strength test and a hop test battery to assess functional leg symmetry. Single leg hop for distance (SLHD) is the most frequently reported functional test.7 A Leg Symmetry Indexleg symmetry index (LSI) of >90% is recommended as a cut-off point indicating safe RTP.8 Athletes who do not meet the discharge criteria before returning to professional sport have a four times greater risk of sustaining an ACL graft rupture compared with those who met all RTSP criteria.9

However, as deficits have also been documented in the contralateral leg after surgery, the use of a symmetry index that compares against the uninjured leg may not be optimal.10 11 Additionally, measuring hop distance or LSI is not informative of the movement quality nor recovery of knee function after ACLR.

Therefore, the objective of this systematic review and meta-analysis was to identify deficits in lower limb biomechanics during SLHD after ACLR. In this context, the effectiveness of SLHD in the decision for a safe RTP was evaluated.

We adhered to the Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic reviews and Meta-Analyse (PRISMA) PRISMA guidelines12 in search strategy and reporting, and followed guidance of the Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews13 for the preparation of this review. The protocol was registered in the PROSPERO database (http://www.crd.york.ac.uk/PROSPERO) (CRD42018087779).
body.title: Search methods
body.p: A systematic search of eight electronic databases (Pubmed (Ovid), EMBASE, CINAHL, Scopus, Web of Science, PEDro, SPORTDiscus and Cochrane Library) was conducted (AK) from inception to 1 April 1stfirst 2018. Grey literature was searched via OpenGrey, as well as the following trial registries: EU Clinical Trials Register, Clinical Trials.gov and WHO International Clinical Trials Registry Platform. The strategy used a range of keywords in four categories which were combined: (1) anterior cruciate ligamentACL (2) rReconstruction. (3) bBiomechanics and. (4) hHop test (online supplementary file 1).
body.title: Study selection
body.p: No limit on language or publication year was imposed to minimise language and publication bias. No minimal duration of follow-up was considered for inclusion. Articles were imported into EndNote V.X7 (Clarivate Analytics Software, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania’s , USA) and duplicates were removed. Two reviewers (AK and VK) independently reviewed the articles by title and abstract using predetermined eligibility criteria. The full texts of potentially eligible studies were retrieved and independently screened. Disagreements were resolved by consensus, or by consulting a third reviewer (RW). Reference lists were also screened (backward citation tracking and the ‘similar function’ within the PubMed database was used) along with the authors’ personal databases.14
Inclusion criteria:

list-item.p: u Studies examining: kinematic, kinetic, and/or EMG data of the ACLR knee and the asymptomatic controls during SLHD test.
u Men and women with ACL rupture managed with reconstruction using any type of graft.

u Observational study designs (prospective cohort studies, case-control studies, and cross-sectional studies) or randomizedrandomised clinical trials (RCTs) with comparison to a control group or to contralateral uninjured side at baseline or at follow-up.
u No restriction was placed on: age, time since surgery, or recruitment method.

body.p: Exclusion criteria

list-item.p: u Abstracts, reviews, case series, case studies, opinion articles, or conference proceedings.
u Studies focusing on other tasks such as drop-jumps, jumping, pivoting, and any sub-maximal tests.

body.title: Assessment of methodological quality
body.p: Two independent reviewers (AK and VK) assessed the methodological quality of included studies using a modified version of the Downs and Black checklist15 as previously described.16 17 The modified version consists of 16 items with a total possible score of 19. A score of ≥75% indicates high quality (HQ), 60%–74% indicates moderate quality (MQ) and ≤60% low quality (LQ).17 Discrepancy between reviewers at initial rating was resolved through discussion, otherwise, a third reviewer (RW) was consulted.
body.title: Data extraction
body.p: Data from included studies were extracted independently by two reviewers (AK and VK). Extracted details from all studies included: authors, year of publication, study design, demographics (age, height, weight, graft type, time since surgery, numbers of participants), primary (kinematics, kinetics, EMG) and any secondary outcomes. Primary outcomes were categorizedcategorised and reported according to the phase of the hop test; propulsion phase (before initial contact (IC)), IC (discrete point) and landing phase (after IC). As there was heterogeneity in the definitions for these phases, propulsion was defined as the time between maximum knee flexion and toe-off, while landing was the time between initial contactIC and maximum knee flexion. If insufficient data were reported in the published article or supplementary material provided, the corresponding author was contacted to request further data. When it was not possible to retrieve data, results were not included in the meta-analysis and were reported descriptively. Where studies reported results of the group of interest (ACLR) during SLHD test but examining different situations, these were included only for qualitative analysis. Where included studies reported participants’ characteristics from another published study, the data from that study was were used. If necessary, authors were contacted for further clarification to confirm eligibility and facilitate accurate data extraction.
body.title: Data analysis
body.p: Extracted data were imported to Review Manager vV.5.3 (RevMan) (Copenhagen: The Nordic Cochrane Centre, The Cochrane Collaboration, 2014) for analysis. Data were analysed by limb using two comparisons: (1) tThe ACLR limb compared tocompared with the contralateral uninjured limb and. (2) tThe ACLR limb compared tocompared with a healthy control group. Means and standard deviations (SDs) from each variable of interest were used to calculate standardizedstandardised mean differences (SMDs) with associated 95% confidence intervals (CIs) in a random-effects model. Cohen’s criteria were used to interpret pooled SMD: large effect ≥0.8, moderate effect 0.5–0.8, and small effect 0.2–0.5.18 The I2 Index INDEX index was used to assess statistical heterogeneity between pooled results and values were interpreted as: low ≤50%; moderate=51%–74% and large ≥75%0.19 Kinematic results were also analysed and reported as mean differences (MDs) for clinical applicability.20 Where standard error (SE)SE or confidence intervals (CIs) were reported, we used the calculator in Review Manager to estimate SD. Joint moments reported as internal were arbitrarily converted to external moments for consistency (eg, internal extension moment=external flexion moment). Where comparing with the control group and if bilateral results were mentioned (dominant – non-dominant), we used data from the dominant leg. When more than one study reported results for the same variable,21 data were pooled in a meta-analysis, otherwise a qualitative synthesis was conducted. All studies eligible for meta-analysis were ordered in forest plots based on time since surgery.21 Sensitivity and subgroup analyses were conducted, where applicable. Levels of evidence were based on recommendations by van Tulder et al22 in alignment with previous reviews of similar included study types23 24 and defined as:

list-item.p: u Strong: consistent results from multiple studies, including a minimum of two high quality (HQ) studies, which are statistically homogeneoous (I2 <50%).

u Moderate: consistent results from multiple studies, including at least one HQ study, which are statistically heterogeneous (I2 >50%); or from multiple moderate/low quality (MQ/LQ) studies which are statistically homogenous (I2 <50%).
u Limited: based on results from multiple MQ and LQ studies which are statistically heterogeneous (I2 >50%); or two MQ/LQ studies statistically homogeneous (I2 <50%); or from one HQ study.
u Very limited: based on results derived from one MQ/LQ study.
u No evidence: if the pooled data were not statistically significant and from multiple statistically heterogeneous (I2 >50%) studies with inconsistent findings.

body.title: Search results
body.p: The electronic search conducted on 1 April 1stfirst 2018, yielded a total of 1551 potentially relevant articles. After duplicate removal, 756 articles were screened by title and abstract. The full texts of 60 articles were assessed for eligibility according to the inclusion/exclusion criteria. Finally, 19 articles25–43 met the inclusion criteria of the present review (Figure 1figure 1).

body.title: Characteristics of the included studies
body.p: Eighteen of the 19 included studies had a cross-sectional design25–32 34–43 and one had a prospective design.33 A total of 624 ACLR patients (424 men, 200 women; mean age 30 years) as well as 315 controls (208 men, 107 women; mean age 27.6 years) were included in the review (table 1). In 13 studies, biomechanical outcomes were compared with the contralateral leg and in 12 studies with a control group. Sixteen studies25 27–32 35–43 reported kinematics of the SLHD test, 8eight studies26 30 33 35 36 39 41 42 reported kinetics, and 4four studies25 27 30 34 reported EMG data. Only two studies27 30 simultaneously collected kinematics, kinetics, and EMG, but one27 used a mixed group of healthy and ACLR patients and compared different landing strategies, whereas another30 reported kinematics and kinetics in a mixed group of healthy and ACLR subjects (due to missing data). Fourteen studies were eligible for meta-analysis. Two studies31 37 made a different analysis of the same data set of a study38 which was used in the meta-analysis, thus those two were included only for qualitative analysis. Also, their sample population was not included in the total ACL patients and controls. Additionally, two studies42 43 used the same data set and the sample calculated only once. Two studies did not compare to with the contralateral leg or a healthy control group but investigated different landing strategies.27 32 Two corresponding authors provided additional information regarding their studies.29 42 Data from one study34 could not be exported and the results were excluded from meta-analysis. A summary of the included studies is presented in table 2. Extracted data include activity level, knee function score and LSI of the hopped distance.

td.p: Successful feed-forward strategies following ACLR were related to graft selection; HST subjects with superior knee function activated their quadriceps earlier and were better able to synchronise peak hamstring muscle activity closer to initial ground contact whilstwhile more functional PT subjects demonstrated enhanced tibial control despite a lack of evidence supporting modified pre-programmed muscular activation patterns.

Better functioning individuals used sensory feedback to build treatment -specific, feed-forward strategies to compensate for varying levels of mechanical instability, when performing a task known to stress the ACL.

Aiming to identify if different activities challenge ACLR patients differently compared tocompared with controls. Knee range of motion was increased more during squatting, intermediately during hopping, but less during gait (Pp<0.01). Peak internal knee extensor moments were highest during distance hop (Pp<0.01). The mean value of peak knee moments was reduced in squatting and gait (Pp<0.01) compared tocompared with hop. Peak internal extensor moments were significantly larger during squatting than gait and peak external adductor moments during gait compared tocompared with squatting (Pp<0.01). Fluency was highest during squatting (Pp<0.01). All patients demonstrated good recovery of gait but anterior cruciate ligamentACL -deficient subjects adopted a strategy of increased fluency (Pp<0.01). During squatting, knee range of motion and peak internal knee extensor moment were reduced in all patients (Pp<0.01). Both patient groups hopped a shorter distance (Pp<0.01) and had reduced knee range of motion (Pp<0.025).

Double leg squat (DLS) and gait should be incorporated early in rehabilitation as loading was comparable but these activities have different roles. DLS permits loading over a larger range of motion, from a stable double stance position and specifically targets knee extension whilstwhile gradually increasing squat depth. Gait loads the knee over a small range of motion but potentially challenges knee control due to the single leg stance. SLDHSLHD was the most challenging activity and bothACLR and ACLDsubjects demonstrated reduced performance and biomechanical compensation strategies. Predictably, SLDHSLHD should be used in the advanced rehabilitation stage as it challenges knee joint motion, moments, and control.

Two distinct rotatory landing strategies found at the initial contact period, internal ITR and external tibial rotation. Those adopting internal tibial rotation (ITR) strategy exhibited significantly larger hopping distance and knee strength. Also, they hopped faster with straighter knees at foot contact and with larger ITR and less knee adduction angular displacement during the initial landing phase.. Proportion of subjects that adopted internal rotation strategy was 20% for injured leg, 10% for uninjured leg, 34.6% in basketball players and 6.5% in the control group.

ITRnternal tibial rotation landing strategy is reported to be the main mechanism for ACL injury. Single-leg hop test can be used as a screening test for ITR landing strategy, by observing the extent of toe-out or knee flexion at the instant of foot contact during single-leg hopping. Potentially hop tests can be used as predictors of dynamic knee stability.

Similar results were found for quantity of movement (strength measurements) comparing operated and healthy subjects. For quality of movement, only the occurrence of dynamic knee valgus in landing from a jump is higher in operated subjects compared with healthy controls.
Focus on quality of movement as part of ACLR rehabilitation programsprogramme and return to sports criteria.
In ACL-reconstructed limbs, significantly earlier onset times were found for all muscles, except vastus medialis, compared with the uninvolved side.
Asymmetries in muscle activation onset between ACLR and contralateral leg during SLHD. These changes may theoretically predispose to reinjury of the ACL.

Determining the effect of an internal or external attentional focus on jump distance and knee kinematics. The external focus group had significantly larger knee flexion angles at initial contact, peak knee flexion, total ROM, and time to peak knee flexion for the injured leg.

Demonstrates the applicability of using an external focus during rehabilitation of patients after ACLR to enhance safer movement patterns compared tocompared with an internal focus of attention and subsequently may help to reduce second ACL injury risk.

Functional data analysis identified specific functional knee-joint deviations from controls persisting 20 years post anterior cruciate ligament-ACL rupture, especially when treated conservatively. This type of analysis has the advantage of considering the entire time-varying structure of kinematic data, identifying relative time intervals in which compromised knee movement patterns are evident.

Applying FDA to movements like the one- leg hop is feasible and, if applied earlier in the rehabilitation process, could guide clinical decision-making by emphasizingemphasising deficiencies throughout the duration of any task.

Using a new motion analysis instrument (2D TIP) to assess landing strategy in ACLR patients, two different landing strategies were defined: a telescopic strategy, which requires increased (internal) knee extensor moments and is used by healthy subjects; and a pendular strategy which requires (internal) flexor moment and is used mostly by ACL -deficient patients. Argument made that ACLR patients at 6 months from surgery and still under rehabilitation therapy, are recovering towards the healthy strategy.

The 2D TIP instrument has demonstrated appropriate reliability, validity and responsiveness for measuring landing strategy in the clinical setting. The instrument is simple, inexpensive and time- efficient in comparison with 3D motion analysis.

Evaluating lower limb kinetics during gait, sprint and hop tests before and after ACLR. The LSI presented high values (90%) at almost all times before and after ACLR in gait, sprint, and single leg hop tests (p<0.005), with a tendency to increase postoperatively. A lower LSI was observed (<90%) in tests where both extremities were tested simultaneously, such as the drop vertical jump and vertical hop tests (p<0.05).

The isolation of the involved and uninvolved limb seems to be a critical component in the functional rehabilitation and evaluation before and after ACLR, as the uninjured leg may tend to compensate in activities where both limbs are under stress at the same time.

Group with better subjective knee function and higher perceived sport activity intensity had more involved gluteus maximus and medial hamstring activation amplitude during propulsion and landing, than the group with lower subjective knee function.

Adaptive hip compensations may be related to a permanent neurosensory deficit and CNS sensimotor re-organizationorganisation. Rehabilitation should focus also on CNS re-education and not only on peripheral neuromuscular function.

During propulsion knee motion was significantly reduced compared with the unnoninvolved leg (Pp=0.008). Peak moments and powers were lower at the knee and higher at the ankle and hip (side by jointSide by Joint Pp=0.011; Pp=0.003, respectively). The peak total extensor moment was not different between legs (Pp=0.305) despite a decrease in knee moment and increases in ankle and hip moments (Side by Joint side by joint Pp=0.015). During landing, knee motion was reduced (Pp=0.043), and peak power absorbed was decreased at the knee and hip and increased at the ankle compared tocompared with the unnoninvolved side (pP=0.003).

Clinicians should be aware that hop ratios based on distance can be deceiving because equivalent performances are not necessarily indicative of similar biomechanics between the involved and unnoninvolved legs. The compensations by other joints may indicate protective adaptations to avoid overloading the reconstructed knee.

Hop distance was less for ACLR (p<0.001; ACLR 75.1±17.8; C 77.7%±14.07% height). ACLR used a similar kinematic strategy to healthy control group but had a reduced peak knee flexion moment (p<0.001; ACLR 0.31±0.16; C 0.42±0.13 BWweight.height). Fluency was reduced in ACLR patients (p=0.006; ACLR 0.14±0.34; C 0.17±0.41 s).

Other pParameters other than hopping distance need to be used for the evaluation of ACLR patients’ recovery such as movement strategies and mediolateral knee control. A telescopic deceleration strategy should be promoted.

td.p: A study with the same ACLR and control group measured in Tengman et al.,38 but with different analysis of the results. Investigating the coordination variability of the hip-knee joint couplings, they found that the ACL group differed significantly from controls on their injured side with ~50% higher knee abduction-adduction/hip internal-external rotation variability during the take-off phase;~33% higher knee abduction-adduction/knee flexion-extension variability and more knee abduction-adduction/hip flexion-extension variability (ACLR 50%) during the landing phase. There were no major differences between injured and non-injured sides.

Coordination variability increased in ACLR compared with controls, no difference between legs and LSI in distance hopped >90%, indicate a poor joint control in ACLR, even 20 years after injury. If estimation of coordination variability becomes more user-friendly, this could be a useful tool for clinical assessment.

Kinematic analysis 20 years after ACL injury or reconstruction. Unlike controls, ACL-injured displayed leg asymmetries: less knee flexion and less internal rotation at take-off and landing and more lateral COM related to knee and ankle joint of the injured leg at landing. Compared toCompared with controls, ACLR had larger external rotation of the injured leg at landing. The ACL- injured leg showed less knee flexion and larger external rotation at take-off and landing, and larger knee abduction at landing. COM was more medial in relation to the knee at take-off and less laterally placed relative to the ankle at landing.

Apart from tibial rotation, ACLR appears to regain a more normalizednormalised movement pattern comparable with that of controls, suggesting that reconstructive surgery may restore the knee biomechanics to some extent. The movement pattern for ACLPT differs in several variables compared with controls and to with the uninjured leg, indicating compensatory strategies both regarding knee kinematics as well as the placement of COM.

Controls demonstrated more peak knee flexion angle, internal knee extension moment and hip extension moment than ACLR subjects. Within the ACLR group, the healthy limb exhibited greater peak knee flexion, hip flexion, hip extension moment, single hop and triple hops distance, and normalizednormalised quadriceps strength. ACLR patients land with their injured leg in a more extended position during an SLHD when compared tocompared with a control group as well as the uninjured leg.

When evaluating readiness to return to sport, clinicians should use a battery of functional tests and note compensations that may be present in the uninjured limb. Clinicians should especially evaluate knee and hip flexion on both limbs to determine whether the patient might be shifting demands away from the injured limb towards the healthy side.

Of the patients who passed LSI scores >90% for the SLHD, altered movement patterns were present in 60%. No differences were found in movement pattern between males men and femaleswomen. Males Men had a decrease in knee flexion at IC (p=0.018), peak knee flexion (p=0.002), and knee flexion range of motion (ROM) (p=0.017) in the injured leg compared tocompared with the nonun-injured leg. Females Women demonstrated a decrease in peak knee flexion (p=0.011) and knee flexion ROM (p=0.023) in the injured leg compared tocompared with the nonun-iinjured leg. Average LSI scores were 92.4% for males men and 94.5% for femaleswomen.

Although LSI scores were >90%, clinically relevant altered movement patterns were detected in the injured leg compared tocompared with the nonun-injured leg. Clinicians should rely not only on LSI scores but also on movement biomechanics to determine RTSreturn to sport readiness.
Biomechanical differences between symmetrical and asymmetrical ACLR patients in terms of LSI. Regardless of hop distance symmetry, patients offload the ACLR knee 5–12 months after surgery.

Hop distance symmetry may not be an adequate test of single limb function and return to sport readiness. During return to sport assessment, movement biomechanics should be considered in addition to hop distance symmetry.

Sagittal plane kinematics and isokinetic strength deficits persist 6 to– 9 months after ACLR using a PT autograft. Compared toCompared with the control group, the ACLR group had greater isokinetic knee extension torque deficits at all speeds (Pp≤0.001) and greater performance asymmetry for all 3three hop tests (Pp<0.001). Compared toCompared with the unnoninvolved lower extremity, the injured leg exhibited less ankle dorsiflexion and knee flexion in the phases of propulsion (Pp≤0.014) and landing (Pp≤0.032). When compared tocompared with the control group, the involved lower extremity exhibited less ankle dorsiflexion in the propulsion phase (Pp<0.001) but higher hip flexion in the landing phase (Pp=0.014).

Suggests a need for more functional interventions to assist ACLR patients to safely return to sports. The ability to attenuate ground reaction forces, restore symmetrical landing patterns, and increase knee extensor muscle strength may be facilitated by rehabilitation that emphasizesemphasises sport-specific exercises and neuromuscular training.

Significant positive correlations between the LSI of the single- limb hop distance and the LSI of the peak extension torque at 120°/s (Pp=0.044, r=0.37) and the peak extension torque at 180°/s (Pp=0.042, r=0.38) as well as a negative correlation with the peak flexion torque at 180°/s (Pp=0.043, r = −0.38). LSI of the single- limb hop test was not correlated with any kinetic or kinematic variable (Pp>0.05).

Performance on the single- limb hop test may be an additional method for evaluating muscle strength asymmetries when isokinetic devices are not available. However, the single- limb hop test cannot be used for evaluating kinetic and kinematic asymmetries.

body.title: Assessment of methodological quality
body.p: The Kappa’sκ correlation coefficient was 0.91 for the agreement between the two reviewers for methodological quality assessment. Quality score ranged from 10 to 17 (maximum score 19) with an average score of 14 (table 2 and online supplementary file 2online supplementary file 2). Justification for scoring for each criterion is presented in online supplementary file 3. There were 9 HQ,28 29 32 34 36 38 39 41 43 6 MQ26 27 30 31 37 40 and 4 LQ25 33 35 42 studies. All included studies reported their aims/hypothesies, main outcomes, participant characteristics and used valid and reliable assessment and outcome tools. Only two studies29 40 attempted to blind one of the assessors. The most frequent sources of potential bias were: source of population of the groups (n=14), no or limited adjustment for potential confounders (n=12) and no power analysis (n=10).

body.p: Two studies25 30 investigated the timing of muscle activity onset relative to IC in comparison to controls. body.title: Qualitative synthesis
body.p: A number of other biomechanical variables were reported across all three lower limb joints, all three planes of motion, during different phases of the SLHD. However, most were reported in a single study and were therefore unable to be pooled. (oOnline supplementary file 5)
body.title: Subgroup analysis
body.p: Subgroup analysis according to time since surgery was performed. The time point was arbitrarily set at 7 months after surgery when patients after ACLR are often discharged from care. Pooled data showed strong evidence of a small effect for decreased peak knee flexion angle during landing both for ACLR patients up to 7 months after surgery (ES: −0.41, CI: −0.64 to −0.18)29 40 41 43 and more than 7 months (ES: −0.28, CI: −0.54 to −0.02),28 38 39 when compared tocompared with the contralateral leg. Interestingly, when compared tocompared with controls, there was no difference (ES: −0.05, CI: −0.90 to −0.80)41 found for patients up to 7 months and a moderate effect (ES: −0.50, CI: −0.73 to −0.28)28 38 39 for those who were more than 7 months after surgery. Similarly, for peak knee abduction angle in landing comparing withto the contralateral leg, no difference (ES: −0.09, CI: −0.78 to 0.60)29 was found for patients up to 7 months and a moderate effect (ES: −0.39, CI: −0.73 to −0.04)38 39 for those who were more than 7 months after surgery (online supplementary file 6).

This systematic review documented kinematic, kinetic, and EMG deficits at a range of time points post-surgery. A key finding was that achieving symmetrical single leg hop distanceSLHD did not ensure symmetry in kinematic and kinetic variables (figure 6).

body.p: While the majority of ACLR patients demonstrated 85%–95% LSI for distance during SLHD test, there are a range of biomechanical deficits in most of the outcomes compared with the contralateral leg. From a clinical perspective, given the high rate of re-injury and contralateral ACL rupture (19% and 22%, respectively, in young athletes)3 and the low rate of athletes returning to their previous level of activity (67%),2 these individual differences warrant further investigation. Kinematic and kinetic differences are more likely to give us useful information than the simplistic aggregate ‘distance hopped’.
body.title: Kinematics
body.p: Lower limb biomechanics of ACLR patients differed from both the contralateral leg and the control group. Specifically, during landing the reconstructed limb had less peak knee flexion, internal rotation, and knee flexion ROM (4.2°, 3.4° and 3.9°, respectively) when compared tocompared with the contralateral leg, with larger effect size (effect sizesES) and absolute values for peak knee internal rotation and knee flexion ROM when compared with controls. The ACLR limb landed with less peak knee abduction compared with the uninjured leg, but no difference was found compared with controls.

Two studies used biplane fluoroscopy to record six degree of freedom6 df tibiofemoral joint kinematics during single leg hop landing (although not max hop for distance) in people with unilateral ACLR.45 46 Biplanar fluoroscopy is the current gold standard for recording joint kinematics during dynamic functional activities. Interestingly, both studies demonstrate reduced knee flexion and less internal rotation for the ACLR limb relative to the unaffected limb, but no difference between limbs in knee ab-duction/adduction. These findings are largely consistent with results for knee frontal and transverse plane motions reported in the current review. We report no differences in trunk kinematics. We speculate that the decreased knee flexion angles may be due to altered quadriceps activation, which is selectively affected at 45° of knee flexion47 or decreased quadriceps strength,43 which could result in landing with a more upright position.45

From a clinical prospective, a ‘stiff’ landing strategy in ACLR patients, with less knee ROM during landing, can result in larger stress on the ACL. Patients should be trained to use ‘soft’ landings.48 Subgroup analysis revealed that some kinematic variables (peak knee flexion and peak knee adduction) do not seem to return to ‘normal’, and may even deteriorate with time. It should be noted that the differences reported, while statistically significant, are relatively small, and likely not detectable with the naked eye. Further, for these measures the minimum clinically important difference is not known.
body.title: Kinetics
body.p: Patients with ACLR produce lower knee and hip flexion moments when landing. Compared toCompared with healthy individuals, ACLR patients land with greater knee adduction moments. Pooled results showed moderate evidence of no difference in the magnitude of GRF. Since moments were different (comparing ACLR to the uninjured leg and the control group), we speculate that moment arms were larger in the ACLR patients. Oberländer et al49 reported that the ACLR leg landed with a more flexed trunk compared tocompared with the uninvolved leg. By flexing their trunk, the GRF vector was shifted anteriorly in relation to the knee, ankle, and hip joint axis, leading to a shift of the joint moment output from the knee to the adjacent joints. Pooled data in our review, however, showed strong evidence of no difference in trunk kinematics during landing.

Wren et al,41 classified their cohort of ACLR subjects as symmetrical or asymmetrical according to LSI during SLHD. During landing, the operated limb, regardless of hop distance, exhibited lower knee flexion moments compared tocompared with controls and the contralateral side with lower knee energy absorption than the contralateral side. Both symmetrical and asymmetrical patients offloaded the operative knee; symmetrical patients achieved symmetry, in part, by hopping a shorter distance on the contralateral side.

Letchford et al,32 using a telescopic inverted pendulum model, defined two different landing strategies: i(1) tThe “‘telescopic’”, which requires greater knee flexion moments, and was used by healthy subjects, and. (2ii) tThe “‘pendular’”, which required extension moments and was used mostly by ACL- deficient patients. The authors argued that ACLR patients at 6 months after surgery and still under rehabilitation, were recovering towards the strategy of healthy individuals.

The present data suggest that restoring symmetry in hop distance does not ensure that knee kinematics and kinetics are restored after ACLR. It is suggested that at least in addition to hop distance, kinematics and kinetics should be considered as RTP criteria. Preliminary, but clinically relevant, evidence from a recent case study50 assessing biomechanical parameters during an SLHD test before ACL injury and 27 months after reconstruction support this approach of examining subject-specific differences incurred as a result of ACL injury, rather than relying on group means.

There is not enough evidence to draw strong conclusions regarding muscle activity patterns in ACLR patients during SLHD. The two studies available are too heterogenous - —partially due to the difference in time since surgery: Gokeler et al30 assessed the patients at 6 months after surgery, while Bryant et al25 evaluated them 1 year after surgery. Likely, muscle activation patterns and strategies following ACLR change with time and influenced by post-operative pain, arthrogenic muscle inhibition, fear of movement, and other factors.51 52

While the evidence is limited regarding alteration in muscle activation, some preliminary observations can be made regarding knee and hip muscle activation differences and possible mechanisms. It has been suggested that the importance of early hamstring activation prior to impact is diminished when anterior knee stability is restored.25 However, this finding confirms the notion that neuropathways other than those mediated by mechanoreceptors within the normal ACL must exist and coordinate hamstring muscle activity.53 On the other hand, perceived higher- level sports capability compared tocompared with pre-knee -injury status was associated with increased lower extremity neuromuscular compensations through hip muscle groups such as gluteus maximus and medial hamstrings.34 Gluteus maximus plays a significant role in frontal plane motion at the hip and may limit excessive dynamic knee valgus.54 Nevertheless, greater fear of re-injury is associated with greater quadriceps pre-activation leading to stiffened movement patterns and potential risk factors of secondary ACL injury.52 Since ACL reconstruction restores mechanical, but not necessarily neurosensory function,55 rehabilitation could focus more on central nervous system re-education rather than solely attempting to optimizeoptimise peripheral neuromuscular function.34
body.title: Assessment of methodological quality and level of evidence
body.p: The methodological quality of included studies was relatively adequate with the majority presenting moderate MQ to high qualityHQ. Four quality domains were the most frequent sources of methodological considerations and bias: blinding of outcome assessors, lack of adjustment for confounders, lack of power analysis and sample size calculation, and selection bias resulting from the lack of description of source of patient population. Pooled data for kinematics showed high and moderate levels of evidence, while regarding kinetics the levels of evidence were more variable. However, the level of evidence was judged as low for a notable number of kinetics, kinematics, and EMG data retrieved from single studies.
body.title: Limitations
body.p: While the levels of evidence provide a synthesis of the quality, quantity, and homogeneity of study results, all relevant studies, regardless of methodological quality, were included. Therefore, we acknowledge the potential bias through the inclusion of poor quality and/or biasedbiassed studies. Also, a funnel plot for assessment of publication bias was not created due to the small number of included studies for each dependent variable. Moreover, there are not enough data available to subgroup our findings according to graft type used. This review was registered (PROSPERO reg no: CRD42018087779) and conducted examining all hop tests in ACL-R patients. In this paper we have only reported the results of the single leg hop for distanceSLHD. The research in this area includes: hop for maximal distance, sub-maximal hop for distance (eg, hopping 50% of limb length), hopping over obstacles, triple hop, side- hop, and drop jump testing. The current review has included only the results of the SLHD in part because of our perception regarding clinical applicability, and in part because of word count limits for the journal. Future research can report these alternate hop test results in a similar manner. Data for knee joint kinematics have been obtained from skin -mounted motion capture systems that are affected by soft tissue artifactartefact (skin/muscle movement with respect to underlying bone) especially during high-impact tasks. This issue limits the ability of skin -mounted motion capture systems to accurately track small secondary joint motions such as knee varus/valgus and axial rotation. Moreover, five studies used 2two-dimensional equipment for data collection.28–30 32 40 Three of these studies28 29 40 reported knee flexion and adduction angles and were included in the meta-analysis, although sensitivity analysis appeared to show that these studies didn't influence the main results from our systematic review (online supplementary file 7online supplementary file 7). The differences in muscle activation patterns have not been as deeply analysed as have those for kinematics and kinetics therefore we are unable to adequately inform practitioners regarding appropriate muscle activation strategies. Importantly it remains to be seen if normalizationnormalisation of these movement patterns is associated with enhanced clinical outcomes. The requirement of relatively expensive equipment, and time and expertise to conduct such analyses, remain a significant barrier to overcome for most clinicians, especially given the current lack of evidence of efficacy or effectiveness for any interventions addressing these biomechanical differences.
body.title: Clinical implications and future research
body.p: Deficits in kinematics and kinetics were detected in patients after ACLR during SLHD. It seems from first principles that it would be wise for clinicians and patients to consider correcting these deficits before RTP. Note that we have no prospective data to suggest this will lower the rate of recurrence of ACL injury or contralateral injury.

These deficits should be analysed and addressed within rehabilitation. Detecting and correcting altered landing strategies should be part of a more individualised rehabilitation programprogramme. Further research is needed to draw strong conclusions on the biomechanical adaptations after ACLR during a range of functional tests to establish if these differences are time-dependent and if asymmetries are associated with clinical outcomes – —specifically does restoration of knee function result in lower re-injury rates.

Whether different surgical approaches (eg, hamstring autograft vs patellar tendon, lateral tenodesis, etc.) influence the elements we have described in this study, is outside our scope. These investigations would require longitudinal study designs. We suggest that reporting only discrete distance values does not adequately characterizecharacterise the quality of movement. Muscle activation patterns have not been examined in any great depth. Since relatively large cohorts will be required, and ACL injury is relatively rare, standardised reporting is recommended to allow pooling of data.

Comparing to with the uninjured leg differed from comparing with healthy controls. Examining the effect sizesES of differences, where possible, the largest difference was noted in knee moment (−0.8 cf −0.6) with relatively minor differences in kinematics, and not enough information for EMG. Therefore, we suggest that a key component of future research is inclusion of knee moment estimation. Unfortunately for the practicing clinician, this currently requires specializedspecialised equipment and analyses.

During SLHD several kinematic and kinetic deficits were detected between limbs after ACLR, despite adequate SLHD performance. Measuring only hop distance, even using the healthy leg as a reference, is insufficient to fully assess knee function after ACLR.

list-item.p: The rate of reinjury after ACL reconstructed (ACLR) is high.
Failure to achieve some simple functional tests are associated with elevated risk of reinjury.
A symmetrical SLHD test does not indicate restoration of normal lower -limb kinematics or kinetics.
ACLR patients tend to offload their reconstructed knee, landing with less knee flexion, less knee flexion moments, and less knee energy absorption (“‘stiff landing’” strategy).
Achieving >90% hop distance for the ACLR leg compared tocompared with the uninjured leg is usually associated with compensatory movements at the hip, ankle, and/or knee joints.
